        <div class="at-above-post addthis-toolbox at-wordpress-hide" data-title="Beyond Resilience  The Rise of the Antifragile" data-url="http://thequintessentialman.com/beyond-resilience-the-rise-of-the-antifragile/">
        </div>
        <div class="at-above-post-recommended addthis-toolbox at-wordpress-hide" data-title="Beyond Resilience  The Rise of the Antifragile" data-url="http://thequintessentialman.com/beyond-resilience-the-rise-of-the-antifragile/">
        </div>
        <p>
         <img alt="antifragile" class="aligncenter wp-image-1230 size-full" height="825" src="http://thequintessentialman.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/Littlefinger.jpg" width="1467"/>
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         Sometimes life can be quite tough. You may experience unforeseen circumstances. You may not have mitigated the risks of your actions. Or you may just end up in the wrong place at the wrong time. The point is that it is impossible to predict any given situation or every possible outcome of your actions.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         It is part of the complexity called life and universe. And you know what? This happens for a reason. The reason is to understand and embrace this complexity. This complexity is what created you and what inspired others to look beyond it and create marvels.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         Take a look around you. Notice the items in your room. From your laptop, to your desk and also the amenities in your house. Take a look outside your window. Everything you see, all these inventions are there because people embraced this complexity and decided to create something useful with it. They were inspired by challenges that this complexity was imposing and were smart enough to think  wait a minute I can make something valuable out of it.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         These were people like you and me. Living their everyday lives, facing challenging obstacles and trying to have a purposeful reality. Complexity will always be there. It will always try to intrude our emotional state and remind us that nothing is easy even if we think it is.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         So how do we actually deal with this situation?
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         What is the most effective way to embrace complexity in our lives and keep challenging ourselves even if the circumstances are kind of knotty?
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         Well the answer to this question is one and only:
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <blockquote>
         <p>
          You have to be resilient. Or maybe you know what. You have to be more than that. You have to be what I like to call anti-fragile.
         </p>
        </blockquote>
        <h1 style="text-align: center;">
        </h1>
        <h1 style="text-align: center;">
        </h1>
        <h1 style="text-align: center;">
        </h1>
        <h1 style="text-align: center;">
         The rise of the Anti-fragile
        </h1>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         Anti-fragile is a word that doesnt exist in dictionaries. It is a term introduced by the brilliant
         <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0812979680/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0812979680&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=thequinman-20&amp;linkId=COMBLQTGIZKQULPG" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0812979680/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0812979680&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=thequinman-20&amp;linkId=COMBLQTGIZKQULPG', 'Nassim Nicholas Taleb']);" target="_blank">
          <span style="text-decoration: underline; color: #0000ff;">
           <span style="text-decoration: underline;">
            Nassim Nicholas Taleb
           </span>
          </span>
         </a>
         , in his book
         <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0812979680/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0812979680&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=thequinman-20&amp;linkId=S4ADKEUF5UPEABFO" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0812979680/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0812979680&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=thequinman-20&amp;linkId=S4ADKEUF5UPEABFO', 'Antifragile: Things that Gain from Disorder']);" target="_blank">
          <span style="text-decoration: underline;">
           <span style="color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;">
            Antifragile: Things that Gain from Disorder
           </span>
          </span>
         </a>
         .
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         For me Nassim Nicholas Taleb is one of the hottest thinkers in the world. He introduced one of these terms in my life that I consider both revolutionary and life changing. It is like having a question about life and not being able to answerit and there comes a man who reveals all his wisdom and gives you the answer you were expecting for so long.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         I am not going to overanalyze what I have read in this book because Taleb approaches the term from a very wide perspective, trying to answer questions like:
         <em>
          Why is the city-state better than the nation-state, why is debt bad for you, and why is what we call efficient not efficient at all? Why should you write your resignation letter before starting on the job? How did the sinking of theTitanicsave lives?
         </em>
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         We will probably need a focus group if we start analyzing all these thoughts.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         So in a nutshell, my understanding of the term is this: You know how human bones get stronger when subjected to stress and tension? The same way, many things in life benefit from stress, disorder, volatility, and turmoil. What Taleb has identified and calls antifragile are things that not only gain from chaos but
         <strong>
          need
         </strong>
         it in order to survive and flourish.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         As very eleganlty the Economist
         <a href="http://www.economist.com/news/books-and-arts/21566619-how-surprises-make-you-stronger-stress-best" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.economist.com/news/books-and-arts/21566619-how-surprises-make-you-stronger-stress-best', 'describes']);" target="_blank">
          <span style="text-decoration: underline;">
           <span style="color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;">
            describes
           </span>
          </span>
         </a>
         it:
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <blockquote>
         <p>
          Antifragility is the secret to success in a world full of uncertainty, a system for turning random mutations to lasting advantage.
         </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         Here comes the million-dollar question though: How does someone become anti-fragile? What are the steps you need to take in order to start empowering your anti-fragile nature?
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         Well there is no simple answer to this, but there are definitely some things you should start considering if you would like to embrace chaos and complexity:
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <hr/>
        <h1 style="text-align: center;">
         1.Understand what efficiency really means and become more efficient in everything you do
        </h1>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         Efficiency. What a widely misunderstood term. I had to go through a lot of stages and career changes in order to understand what efficiency is and how to be properly efficient in whatever I do.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         Efficiency is closely related to discipline and focus. It is the process you need to undertake in order to achieve different goals you have. These goals can range from starting your own business or learning guitar, to mastering the art of seduction.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         Now why is this related to anti-fragility? Well you can consider efficiency a proactive measure. Or maybe the first step to achieving an anti-fragile nature.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <blockquote>
         <p>
          If you have the notion of efficiency well established in your mind, you will become more familiar with the notion of chaos as well. Nobody started becoming efficient without understanding that chaos is part of the efficiency equation.
         </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         From my early years as an electrical engineer student when I had to deal with complex mathematical equations, to my latest entrepreneurial days, chaos was the main parameter in the efficiency equation.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         If I wouldnt embrace it, I would become lost and confused. I would probably give up and question my own abilities and existence.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         As I already mentioned above chaos is there for a reason.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <hr/>
        <h1 style="text-align: center;">
         2. Become a Strategic thinker
        </h1>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         Strategic planning/thinking is also closely related to proactivity, as mentioned above. Most of the strategic thinkers are actually peoplewho are really close to what we call anti-fragile.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <blockquote>
         <p>
          Strategic thinkers like to estimate all the parameters that affect their actions. They are planning ahead in order to minimize the risk of failure and achieve a great outcome in everything they do. They embrace chaos and use it as a ladder.
         </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         They are characterized by the following traits:
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <ul>
         <li>
          They anticipate  they wait until there is the right moment to make a bold move
         </li>
         <li>
          They think critically  question everything
         </li>
         <li>
          They interpret  gather a lot of information before developing a viewpoint
         </li>
         <li>
          They develop processes  use automation as a tool to reduce time consuming activities
         </li>
         <li>
          They align  they engage with the right people
         </li>
         <li>
          They learn from their mistakes  no comment
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
         Being a strategic thinker will get you in a position of anti-fragility in no time.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <hr/>
        <h1 style="text-align: center;">
         3. inject small amounts of stress in your life
        </h1>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         Intentionally try and introduce pressure and stress in your life. By that, I dont mean long-term stress  the kind of stress that consumes your life and distracts you from your main focus. I mean the kind of stress that releases the right hormones so that your body and mind can activate the anti-fragility that is built inside them. Typical examples might include:
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <ul>
         <li>
          Putting personal short-term deadlines in things you want to achieve.
         </li>
         <li>
          Playing competitive video games with friends. (
          <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4uB_8fuSCSQ" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4uB_8fuSCSQ', 'please dont overdo it']);" target="_blank">
           <span style="text-decoration: underline;">
            <span style="color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;">
             please dont overdo it
            </span>
           </span>
          </a>
          )
         </li>
         <li>
          Taking cold showers once in a while.
         </li>
         <li>
          Practicing competitive sports  team or individual.
         </li>
         <li>
          Practicing martial arts.
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
        </p>
        <hr/>
        <h1 style="text-align: center;">
         4. Reduce negativity  Practicevia negativa
        </h1>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         According to Taleb, the first step towards antifragility consists in first decreasing downside. And what is the best place to start? Your social environment of course.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <blockquote>
         <p>
          Stop interacting with people who want to impose negativity in your life. We all have been in situations where we were stuck with people who can offer less than we are expecting. I like to call them
          <a href="http://thequintessentialman.com/great-seducers-others-dont-9-powerful-techniques-can-help-maintain-great-emotional-state/" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article-int', 'http://thequintessentialman.com/great-seducers-others-dont-9-powerful-techniques-can-help-maintain-great-emotional-state/', 'emotional state leeches']);" target="_blank" title="What great seducers do that you dont  9 powerful techniques that can help you maintain a great emotional state">
           <span style="text-decoration: underline; color: #0000ff;">
            emotional state leeches
           </span>
          </a>
          .
         </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         Being anti-fragile doesnt mean you need to keep hanging around them because you have embraced chaos and you think it is a great way to train yourself. Being anti-fragile means to have the balls to say enough and let them out of your life for good. The type of people you should usually avoid are:
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <ul>
         <li>
          The showoffs
         </li>
         <li>
          The leeches
         </li>
         <li>
          The unintelligent
         </li>
         <li>
          The lazy
         </li>
         <li>
          The big talkers
         </li>
         <li>
          The non-believers
         </li>
         <li>
          The non-dreamers
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
         Quintessential Man
         <a href="https://www.facebook.com/PaulHudsonTheOneAndOnly" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'https://www.facebook.com/PaulHudsonTheOneAndOnly', 'Paul Hudson']);" target="_blank">
          <span style="text-decoration: underline; color: #0000ff;">
           Paul Hudson
          </span>
         </a>
         in his article  
         <span style="text-decoration: underline;">
          <span style="color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;">
           <a href="http://elitedaily.com/life/the-10-types-of-toxic-people-that-mentally-strong-people-avoid/" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://elitedaily.com/life/the-10-types-of-toxic-people-that-mentally-strong-people-avoid/', 'The 10 Types Of Toxic People That Mentally Strong People Avoid']);" target="_blank">
            <span style="color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;">
             The 10 Types Of Toxic People That Mentally Strong People Avoid
            </span>
           </a>
          </span>
         </span>
         describes them in an exceptional way.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <hr/>
        <h1 style="text-align: center;">
         5. Consider self-employment
        </h1>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         There is nothing wrong with having a job in a company or an entity where you are just a simple employee. Been there done that.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         Its just whether you like it or not, it is almost impossible to feel responsible for the entity you are working for, if it is not yours.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         Whatever you do, you know that you will always be vulnerable to the entitys decisions. You feel that the entity is like the parent who takes care of the important stuff and you are there just to help a bit.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         This puts you in a position of decreased responsibility and you end up being hypnotized and exposed to the entitys volatility.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         Becoming self-employed is one of the decisions in a mans life that actually skyrockets anti-fragility. Self-employed people are usually:
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <ul>
         <li>
          more responsible
         </li>
         <li>
          more proactive
         </li>
         <li>
          more strategic
         </li>
         <li>
          more intelligent
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
         All these traits are important components of an anti-fragile nature and the most compelling arguments for the support of self-employment.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <hr/>
        <h1 style="text-align: center;">
         Conclusion
        </h1>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         I decided to write this article because I consider anti-fragility one of the most important traits a Quintessential Man must possess.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         I mention it in my
         <a href="http://thequintessentialman.us3.list-manage.com/subscribe?u=63e2e31179572a0854cce44fe&amp;id=ec0d710c31" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://thequintessentialman.us3.list-manage.com/subscribe?u=63e2e31179572a0854cce44fe&amp;id=ec0d710c31', 'ebook']);" target="_blank">
          <span style="text-decoration: underline;">
           <span style="color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;">
            ebook
           </span>
          </span>
         </a>
         where I state how Antifragility has helped me cope with everyday challenges and also embraceobstacles and complex situations. I believe it can help you too.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         I leave you the way I started this article, because the more I listen to
         <a href="http://gameofthrones.wikia.com/wiki/Petyr_Baelish" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://gameofthrones.wikia.com/wiki/Petyr_Baelish', 'Lord Petyr Baelish']);" target="_blank">
          <span style="text-decoration: underline;">
           <span style="color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;">
            Lord Petyr Baelish
           </span>
          </span>
         </a>
         the more antifragile I become.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
         <span class="embed-youtube" style="text-align:center; display: block;">
          <iframe class="youtube-player" frameborder="0" height="424" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/PxlIraEV8n4?version=3&amp;rel=1&amp;fs=1&amp;showsearch=0&amp;showinfo=1&amp;iv_load_policy=1&amp;wmode=transparent" type="text/html" width="700">
          </iframe>
         </span>
        </p>
